@alexjg, I've finally exposed the Cursor API to C programs.

In order to make the full unit test suite pass again, I also included the changes from PR #885 that I authored.

@heckj can either rebase PR #885 onto main after this PR is approved or he can open a new PR for his changes.

Ran into this behavior today and was surprised by it.

```js
    it("does not support undefined values", () => {
      let doc = Automerge.init<any>()
      assert.throws(() => {
        doc = Automerge.change(doc, doc => {
          doc.foo = undefined
        })
      }, "Unsupported type undefined")
    })
```

After some head-scratching I realized that `undefined` is not a valid JSON value. 

The full error message you get is `Unsupported type undefined at path /a/b/c", which wasn't super helpful to me. 

This PR changes the error messages for this and similar situations so that they point the developer in the right direction.

# Rich text RC1

This is a follow up to https://github.com/automerge/automerge/pull/869 which introduced a first stab at a rich text API for automerge, I'll assume everyone has read the discussion on that PR.

The primary difference between this PR and the alpha is that in this PR we don't assume any particular structure on the block markers which are inserted inline. Recall that in the previous PR I had defined a block marker as a map with the following typescript type:

```
type Block = {
    parents: string[],
    type: string,
    attrs: {[key: string]: Value}
}
```

In this PR all that we know is that a block is a map. It is just like any other automerge map. This means that there are also no longer specific patches for splitting, joining, and updating blocks, there are just the standard patches we already have. This is more general but irritating to program against, but solving this programming problem is a problem with the patch API in general and about which I think we have some good ideas - to come later.

The API now looks like this then:

```typscript
function splitBlock<T>(
  doc: Doc<T>,
  path: stable.Prop[],
  index: number | Cursor,
  block: {[key: string]: MaterializeValue},
)

export function joinBlock<T>(
  doc: Doc<T>,
  path: stable.Prop[],
  index: number | Cursor,
)

export function updateBlock<T>(
  doc: Doc<T>,
  path: stable.Prop[],
  index: number | Cursor,
  block: {[key: string]: MaterializeValue},
)

export function spans<T>(doc: Doc<T>, path: stable.Prop[]): Span[] {

export function updateSpans<T>(
  doc: Doc<T>,
  path: stable.Prop[],
  blocks: Span[],
)
```

This more general API deliberately punts on the open questions from the last PR. Automerge won't have an opinion about what rich text should look like exactly and we'll need to form a set of conventions around that, but we won't have to modify automerge to experiment with those conventions.
